I"­<p>GitHub is excellent for code repositories online. GitHub pages is good for making your work available over the internet.</p>

<p>GitHub Pages further pushed me to learn Git, GitHub and Jekyll (blogging with GitHub pages).</p>

<p>These notes can help you setup Git on Mac and link it with GitHub account.</p>

<p>I have followed an excellent <a href="https://kbroman.org/github_tutorial/">post</a> by Karl Broman on the same. You can find summary of his guide below:</p>

<h2 id="1-install-git">1. Install Git</h2>
<p>Git is version controlling that can be installed locally.</p>

<h2 id="2-setup-rsa-for-ssl">2. Setup RSA for SSL</h2>
<p>RSA is used for making safe authentications via SSL.</p>

<h2 id="3-setup-github-account">3. Setup GitHub Account</h2>
<p>You will get an online space to upload your code with version controlling.</p>

<h2 id="4-use-git-and-github">4. Use Git and GitHub</h2>
<p>THis will help you sync your local code repositories with online one.</p>

<h2 id="5-github-pages-and-blogging-with-jekyll">5. GitHub pages and blogging with Jekyll</h2>
<p>Now that you have all set up, you can setup GitHub Pages to launch your site.
Further, if you want to blog on your site you can setup Jekyll.</p>

<p>Follow this post, [Setting Jekyll Now on GitHub] to get started with blogging and personal site.</p>

